      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the slow dance of the principal and the quick steps of the interest, much like a slow-moving tortoise and a sprightly little gnome. When you make your full payments, you're essentially sending a goblin messenger to the loan lender, who then takes a small portion of your payment to cover the interest and sends the rest to the principal. The interest is calculated based on the remaining balance, so if the principal is a large mountain, the interest is a tiny goblin that scurries around, making its rounds. At first, this goblin is quite busy, so the principal mountain doesn't seem to shrink much. But over time, as the goblin gets tired, the mountain slowly starts to crumble. It's a slow process, but eventually, you'll see the principal mountain shrinking, goblin by goblin. Keep making your full payments, and soon you'll see the goblins of interest slowing down, and the principal mountain will start to crumble faster.",
