      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin misdirection. Let's get down to the nitty-gritty of the math, no goblins this time. The formula to calculate the monthly interest on your student loan is typically:\n\nMonthly Interest = (Remaining Principal Balance) x (Annual Interest Rate) / 12\n\nSo, if you have a remaining principal balance of $10,000 and an annual interest rate of 5%, the monthly interest would be:\n\nMonthly Interest = ($10,000) x (0.05) / 12 = $41.67\n\nThis means that out of your monthly payment, $41.67 goes towards paying the interest, and the rest goes towards reducing the principal. The feeling that the balance barely moves at first is because the interest is calculated on the remaining principal, which is still quite large. As you continue to make payments, the principal decreases, and so does the interest, making it easier to see the principal shrinking over time.",
