      "content": "Absolutely, paying extra towards the principal can indeed speed up the process of paying off your loan. To calculate how much time you'd save by adding an extra $100 a month, you'd need to know the total remaining balance of your loan, the interest rate, and the minimum monthly payment. With those details, you can use an amortization calculator or a loan repayment formula to estimate the time savings.\n\nHowever, I can give you a simplified explanation. By paying an extra $100 a month, you're effectively reducing the principal balance by that amount each month, which in turn reduces the interest calculated on the remaining balance. This means that over time, you'll pay less interest and reduce the principal faster, leading to a shorter loan term.\n\nTo get a rough estimate, you could use the following formula:\n\nNew Loan Term = (Remaining Principal Balance) / (Minimum Monthly Payment + Extra Payment)\n\nKeep in mind that this is a simplified calculation and doesn't take into account the changing interest rate or other factors that might affect your loan. For a more accurate estimate, it's best to use an online loan calculator or consult with a financial advisor.",
